 BY BAMIDELE FAMOOFO Access Bank Plc, subsidiary of Nigeria’s Access Corporation, is set to acquire 83.4 percent of Kenya’s Sidan Bank Limited for $37million or N15billion. The Nigerian bank said it has entered into a binding agreement with Kenyan-based Centum Investment Plc to seal the deal. A statement from Access Bank Plc disclosed that Sidan will be merged with Access Bank’s subsidiary in Kenya, Access Bank Kenya, to create a stronger banking institution better positioned to serve the Kenyan market. Herbert Wigwe, Group Chief Executive, Access Corporation said the growth transaction being implemented in Kenya represents the relentless focus and execution of the bank’s strategic objectives within its banking subsidiary even as it grows the other businesses within Access Corporation’s core segments. “The acquisition of Sidan is a significant step-up in scale and potential for Access Bank in Kenya which represents the largest market and trade corridor in East Africa. The significant increase in scale and customer base presents us with enormous opportunities to support growth in the various ecosystems we are building in our trade and payment business. The economies of scale that derive therefrom will continue to drive and enhance contributions to all stakeholders,”Wigwe added. Roosevelt Ogbonna, Chief Executive Officer of Access Bank also said that the transaction builds on the earlier acquisition of the former Transnational Bank Plc (now Access Bank Kenya) and underscores the bank’s resolve to strengthen its presence in Kenya. The deal is however subject to the fulfillment of conditions precedent including regulatory approvals in both Kenya and Nigeria. 